    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1971-10-22T07:05:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1971-10-22T07:05:00-05:00" n="413"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d413">
                <head>413. Telegram 4815 From the <gloss type="from">Embassy in Spain</gloss> to the
                        <gloss type="to">Department of State</gloss>
                    <note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d413fn1">Source: National Archives, <gloss
                            target="#t_RG1">RG</gloss> 59, Central Files 1970-73, POL 33-8. Secret;
                        Priority; <gloss target="#t_Exdis1">Exdis</gloss>.</note>
                    <note n="2" type="summary" xml:id="d413fn2">Ambassador <persName
                            corresp="#p_HRC1">Hill</persName> described his conversation with
                        General <persName corresp="#p_FB2">Franco</persName> after handing him
                        President <persName corresp="#p_NRM1">Nixon</persName>’s letter.</note>
                </head>
                <dateline>
                    <placeName>Madrid</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                        when="1971-10-22T12:05:00+00:00">October 22, 1971, 1205Z</date>.</dateline>
                <list type="references">
                    <head>Ref:</head>
                    <item>State 192158, Madrid 4808</item>
                </list>
                <list>
                    <label>1.</label>
                    <item>At 10:00 am Friday, October 22, I personally presented President <persName
                            corresp="#p_NRM1">Nixon</persName>’s letter regarding the <gloss
                            target="#t_US1">US</gloss> position on the Law of the Sea to the Chief
                        of State, General <persName corresp="#p_FB2">Franco</persName>.</item>
                    <label>2.</label>
                    <item>In a brief cordial conversation with General <persName corresp="#p_FB2"
                            >Franco</persName> and <gloss target="#t_FonMin1">FonMin</gloss>
                        <persName corresp="#p_LBCG1">Lopez Bravo</persName>, I explained to them the
                        great importance the President of the United States attaches to this problem
                        and said I hoped Spain would give the <gloss target="#t_US1">US</gloss>
                        position its full consideration.</item>
                    <label>3.</label>
                    <item>General <persName corresp="#p_FB2">Franco</persName>, upon receiving the
                        letter, stated Spain would seriously consider the matter but he stressed
                        that public opinion in his country would have to be taken into account, in
                        view of the Gibraltar problem.</item>
                    <label>4.</label>
                    <item>General <persName corresp="#p_FB2">Franco</persName> looked well and
                        appeared alert and was most friendly. I also conveyed to him the President’s
                        best personal regards and he asked to have his friendly best wishes extended
                        to President <persName corresp="#p_NRM1">Nixon</persName>.</item>
                </list>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_HRC1">Hill</persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
